ocr.sentence: Πεπτωκότος γὰρ ἐν τῇ μάχῃ τοῦ Ἀχιλλέως ἐδόκουν Αἴας τε καὶ Ὀδυσσεὺς ἐπ’ αὐτῷ πλέον u ἀριστεύειν περὶ τὴν τοῦ σώματος κομιδήν· καὶ κρι- νομένων περὶ τῶν ὅπλων, κρατεῖ Ὀδυσσεὺς, ὅθεν ὁ Αας, τῆς κρίσεως μὴ Tuyav, παρακεκίνηται zul διέ- φθαρται τὴν γνώμην, ὦστε ἐφαπτόμενος τῶν ποιμνίων δοκεῖν τοὺς Ἕλληνας διαχρήσασθαι, καὶ Ta μὲν ἀνεῖλε Tüv τετραπόδων, za δὲ δήσας ἀπάγει ἐπὶ τὴν σκηνὴν, ἐν οἷς ἐστι καὶ κριός τις ἔξοχος, ὃν Wero εἶναι Ὀδυσ- cu, iv δήσας ἐμαστίγωσεν, ὅθεν καὶ τῇ ἐπιγραφῇ πρόςκειται ὁ Μαστιγοφόρος, ἢ πρὸς ἀντιδιαστολὴν τοῦ Λοκροῦ.

groundtruth.sentence: Πεπτωκότος γὰρ ἐν τῇ μάχῃ τοῦ Ἀχιλλέως ἐδόκουν Αἴας τε καὶ Ὀδυσσεὺς ἐπ’ αὐτῷ πλέον τι ἀριστεύειν περὶ τὴν τοῦ σώματος κομιδήν· καὶ κρι- νομένων περὶ τῶν ὅπλων, κρατεῖ Ὀδυσσεὺς, ὅθεν ὁ Αἴας, τῆς κρίσεως μὴ τυχὼν, παρακεκίνηται καὶ διέ- φθαρται τὴν γνώμην, ὥστε ἐφαπτόμενος τῶν ποιμνίων δοκεῖν τοὺς Ἕλληνας διαχρήσασθαι, καὶ τὰ μὲν ἀνεῖλε τῶν τετραπόδων, τὰ δὲ δήσας ἀπάγει ἐπὶ τὴν σκηνὴν, ἐν οἷς ἐστι καὶ κριός τις ἔξοχος, ὃν ᾤετο εἶναι Ὀδυσ- σέα, ὃν δήσας ἐμαστίγωσεν, ὅθεν καὶ τῇ ἐπιγραφῇ πρόςκειται ὁ Μαστιγοφόρος, ἢ πρὸς ἀντιδιαστολὴν τοῦ Λοκροῦ.

In the Middle Ages the Jews were often called, in a way, the “most unclean” Jews, when Jews are described as not being able to understand or even pronounce a “good word”. Their inability to perform this work, however, was not the result of their inability to understand, but rather their own ignorance of the Jewish concept of “good word”. Since the Jews were not a special group of people, this lack of knowledge was compounded by the fact that they were often the only people with a strong Jewish influence in their communities, and since Jews are called by the Jewish people themselves the Jews, this is a major reason for their frequent derogations of Jews in the West, as compared to the “people of Israel”.

groundtruth.region: ΑΘΗΝΑ. ΟΔΥΣΣΕΥΣ. ΑΙΑΣ. ΑΘΗΝΑ. Ἀεὶ μὲν, ὦ παῖ Λἀρτίου, δέδορκά σε πεῖράν τιν’ ἐχθρῶν ἁρπάσαι θηρώμενον καὶ νῦν ἐπὶ σκηναῖς σε ναυτικαῖς ὁρῶ Αἴαντος, ἔνθα τάξιν ἐσχάτην ἔχει, πάλαι κυνηγετοῦντα καὶ μετρούμενον ἴχνη τὰ κείνου νεοχάραχθ’, ὅπως ἴδῃς εἴτ’ ἔνδον, εἴτ’ οὐκ ἔνδον· εὖ δέ σ’ ἐκφέρει κυνὸς Λακαίνης ὥς τις εὔρινος βάσις. ἔνδον γὰρ ἀνὴρ ἄρτι τυγχάνει κάρα στάζων ἱδρῶτι καὶ χέρας ξιφοκτόνους. καί σ’ οὐδὲν εἴσω τῆς δε παπταίνειν πύλης ἔτ’ ἔργον ἐστὶν, ἐννέπειν δ’ ὅτου χάριν σπουδὴν ἔθου τήνδ’, ὡς παρ’ εἰδυίας μάθῃς. ΟΔΥΣΣΕΥΣ. φθέγμ’ Ἀθάνας, φιλτάτης ἐμοὶ θεῶν, ὡς εὐμαθές σου, κἂν ἄποπτος ᾖς, ὅμως φώνημ’ ἀκούω καὶ ξυναρπάζω φρενὶ, χαλκοστόμου κώδωνος ὡς Τυρσηνικῆς. καὶ νῦν ἐπέγνως εὖ μ’ ἐπʼ ἀνδρὶ δυςμενεῖ βάσιν κυκλοῦντ’, Αἴαντι τῷ σακεςφόρῳ.

"dei μὲν, & παῖ Λἀρτίου, δέδορκά os πεῖράν τιν’ ἐχθρῶν ἁρπάσαι θηρώμενον· καὶ νῦν ἐπὶ σκηναῖς σε ναυτικαῖς ὁρῷῶ Αίαντος, ἔνθα τάξιν ἐσχάτην ἔχει, πάλαι κυνηγετοῦντα καὶ μετρούμενον ἴχνη τὰ κείνου νεοχάραχθ’, ὅπως ἴδῃς εἴτ’ ἔνδον, εἴτ’ οὐκ ἔνδον· εὖ δέ σ’ ἐκφέρει κυνὸς Λακαίνης ὥς τις εὔρινος βάσις. ἔνδον γὰρ ἀνὴρ ἄρτι τυγχάνει κάρα στάζων ἱδρῶτι nal χέρας ξιφοκτόνους. καί σ’ οὐδὲν εἴσω τῆςδε παπταίνειν πύλης ἔτ’ ἔργον ἐστὶν, ἐννέπειν δ’ ὅτου χάριν σπουδὴν Edov τήνδ’, ὡς παρ’ εἰδυίας μάθῃς. ΟΔΥΣΣΕΥΣ. Ὦ φθέγμ’ Ἀθάνας, φιλτάτης ἐμοὶ θεῶν, ὡς εὐμαθές σου, κἂν ἄποπτος 6, ὅμως φώνημ’ ἀκούω καὶ ξυναρπάζω φρενὶ, χαλκοστόμου κώδωνος ὡς Τυρσηνικῆς. καὶ νῦν ἐπέγνως εὖ μ’ ἐπ’ ἀνδρὶ δυςμενεῖ βάσιν κυκλοῦντ’, Αἴαντι τῷ σακεςφόρῳ.

ΟΔΥΣΣΕΥΣ. φθέγμ’ Ἀθάνας, φιλτάτης ἐμοὶ θεῶν, ὡς εὐμαθές σου, κἂν ἄποπτος ᾖς, ὅμως φώνημ’ ἀκούω καὶ ξυναρπάζω φρενὶ, χαλκοστόμου κώδωνος ὡς Τυρσηνικῆς. καὶ νῦν ἐπέγνως εὖ μ’ ἐπʼ ἀνδρὶ δυςμενεῖ βάσιν κυκλοῦντ’, Αἴαντι τῷ σακεςφόρῳ.

K. K. V. M. Zemanov was born in the Soviet Union in 1928. A year later, he was arrested and detained in Dnipropetrovsk, the place where he studied law.

Civil Rights Action

In 1989, a civil rights group published an open letter about K. K. V. M. Zemanov. A day after the letter, Zemanov, K. K. V. M. Zemanov and others published a newspaper. An article in the Soviet Times of June 12 was published to criticise the organization of the Civil Rights Action and to urge the creation of a social democratic state. In July, the Civil Rights Action published a newspaper with articles on the same subject as the open letter. The paper was published in the Soviet Union in 1990 and a special issue was published in 1991.
After the death of K. K. V. M. Zemanov in 1990, the Civil Rights Action published a series of articles to criticise the organization of the organization, and published a newspaper with articles on the same subject as the article of the open letter. In March 1992, the civil rights group published a special issue on a similar topic. The special issue was published in the Soviet Union in 1995. The same year, K. K. V. M. Zemanov published a special issue on the same subject.
In September 1992, the Civil Rights Action published a special issue on the same subject. The special issue was published in the Soviet Union in 1995.
In 1997, the Civil Rights Action published a special issue on the same topic. The special issue was published in the Soviet Union in 2000.

An article in the Soviet Times of June 12 was published to criticise the organization of the Civil Rights Action and to urge the creation of a social democratic state. In July, the Civil Rights Action published a newspaper with articles on the same subject as the open letter. The paper was published in the Soviet Union in 1990 and a special issue was published in 1991.
After the death of K. K. V. M. Zemanov in 1990, the Civil Rights Action published a series of articles to criticise the organization of the organization, and published a newspaper with articles on the same subject as the article of the open letter. In March 1992, the civil rights group published a special issue on a similar topic. The special issue was published in the Soviet Union in 1995. The same year, K. K. V. M. Zemanov published a special issue on the same subject.
In September 1992, the Civil Rights Action published a special issue on the same subject. The special issue was published in the Soviet Union in 1995.
In 1997, the Civil Rights Action published a special issue on the same topic. The special issue was published in the Soviet Union in 2000.

Civil Rights Action

A short story in a series of short stories on the work of the same author

Two days later, I went to the local tavern to have a drink. A certain stranger was waiting for me on the porch. I sat on a table in front of him. He was a very smart young man, with a good smile, and a short, very broad, curly, red head, a very pretty, curly, red face, very strong lips, and a beautiful voice.
I was very much surprised to see him. He was wearing the same suit of clothes as the others and was sitting on a very low platform on the porch. It was very fine indeed, and I could see how he liked the place. But there was a gap in his face between the long, high chin and the long thin lips. That was not something that pleased me. I turned to my companion.
He asked me if I liked the place, and then he asked me how I liked it. I was so surprised at this fact that I had to laugh. I had no idea that he was the kind of man who was always having problems with people and people in society. His face was very good, and his lips were pretty strong. I did not know if he had an aunt, or a sister, or anything else.
I looked around the room in a vague sort of way and saw that the young man had no aunt or a sister, and that his eyes were rather small, and that he had a very thin nose. I could see how he was quite unacquainted with the world.

I had no sooner seen this that he had thrown his arms around me, and he was holding up his big, dark, thick beard. I stood back. He looked me down and asked me if I liked the place, and I said that I did not.

He looked very much disturbed at me.

‘What is your name, man?’

‘My name is Karyn.’

‘You are a very clever person, and have a very good taste.’

I was greatly astonished and pleased at this. The whole man was astonished and pleased at this.

‘Are you going to ask me my father to come back with us at night?’

‘We can arrange it.’

‘But you will not be alone, will you, Karyn?’

‘I am going to go with you.’

‘Do not be nervous,’ said the other. He said it quite honestly.

Two days later, I went to the local tavern to have a drink. A certain stranger was waiting for me on the porch. I sat on a table in front of him. He was a very smart young man, with a good smile, and a short, very broad, curly, red head, a very pretty, curly, red face, very strong lips, and a beautiful voice.
I was very much surprised to see him. He was wearing the same suit of clothes as the others and was sitting on a very low platform on the porch. It was very fine indeed, and I could see how he liked the place. But there was a gap in his face between the long, high chin and the long thin lips. That was not something that pleased me. I turned to my companion.
He asked me if I liked the place, and then he asked me how I liked it. I was so surprised at this fact that I had to laugh. I had no idea that he was the kind of man who was always having problems with people and people in society. His face was very good, and his lips were pretty strong. I did not know if he had an aunt, or a sister, or anything else.
I looked around the room in a vague sort of way and saw that the young man had no aunt or a sister, and that his eyes were rather small, and that he had a very thin nose. I could see how he was quite unacquainted with the world.

I had no sooner seen this that he had thrown his arms around me, and he was holding up his big, dark, thick beard. I stood back. He looked me down and asked me if I liked the place, and I said that I did not.

He looked very much disturbed at me.

‘What is your name, man?’

‘My name is Karyn.’

‘You are a very clever person, and have a very good taste.’

I was greatly astonished and pleased at this. The whole man was astonished and pleased at this.

‘Are you going to ask me my father to come back with us at night?’

‘We can arrange it.’

‘But you will not be alone, will you, Karyn?’

‘I am going to go with you.’

‘Do not be nervous,’ said the other. He said it quite honestly.

I did not want to go in a hurry. I was quite certain that he would ask me to come back with us at night. But I could not give him that kind of a reason.

He looked very much surprised and pleased at my answer, and I told him the whole story, all the details. He said it so well that the other man was really impressed.

‘Do you like the place?’
